                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13462766" author="mumrah" created="Tue, 25 Sep 2012 14:20:19 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Here&apos;s a go at a simple fix for this. I added a &quot;name&quot; attribute to the CompressionCodec case objects and added getCompressionCodec(String). &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13468142" author="jjkoshy" created="Tue, 2 Oct 2012 22:44:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for the patch, David.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. Can we make the name match case insensitive? i.e., just name.toLowerCase.match&lt;br/&gt;
2. Any particular reason to change the config name to compression.name? I think compression.codec looks better.&lt;br/&gt;
3. Can you make it backward compatible? i.e., allow both int and string in ProducerConfig. (Also, there are other usages of compression.codec - e.g., in system tests and contrib/hadoop* that still use the int).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13468213" author="mumrah" created="Wed, 3 Oct 2012 00:21:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Joel, thanks for the review.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve changed the config property back to &quot;compression.codec&quot;. It accepts the short names (none, gzip, snappy) as well as the old int values. I also made the name match case insensitive like you suggested. New patch is attached&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13468254" author="jjkoshy" created="Wed, 3 Oct 2012 01:45:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for making that change. ProducerConfig: There&apos;s a compilation error due to getString default being given an int. Also, the second call to getCompressionCodec should have the default as well (or some unit tests will fail). Looks good otherwise.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13468277" author="mumrah" created="Wed, 3 Oct 2012 02:51:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Compilation error - embarrassing. Maybe I should be more careful since I&apos;m still pretty new to Scala.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Fixed those two issues. `sbt compile test` is happy&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13468772" author="jjkoshy" created="Wed, 3 Oct 2012 19:51:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1&lt;br/&gt;
(I don&apos;t think we need to apply this to trunk.) Committed this to 0.8 with a very minor edit.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
